component of pyruvate dehydrogenase.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crigler-Najjar syndrome","Gilbert syndrome","Hepatitis A","Primary biliary cholangitis","Primary sclerosing cholangitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary biliary cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition mainly affects middle-aged women. It is characterised by anti-mitochondrial antibodies targeting pyruvate dehydrogenase and showing characteristic bile duct inflammation with granulomas. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute viral infection that does not typically cause chronic liver disease or autoantibodies. \u003Cstrong\u003EGilbert syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign condition causing unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia without liver inflammation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary sclerosing cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E affects larger bile ducts and is not associated with anti-mitochondrial antibodies. \u003Cstrong\u003ECrigler-Najjar syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a genetic disorder of bilirubin metabolism without inflammatory features.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC) is characterised by anti-mitochondrial antibodies targeting the E2 component of pyruvate dehydrogenase.","PBC features intralobular bile duct inflammation with T lymphocyte infiltration and granulomas.","PBC predominantly affects middle-aged women and presents with liver function tests showing a cholestatic picture."],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","amada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook 